notes_contact1: Spoke with the patient who stated that he is ok. Pt stated that he had a toe amputation recently. Pt stated he lives with siblings who provide good support. Pt stated he won't be able to work for a while per the doctor's recommendation due to his toe amputation.  Pt stated that he is undocumented and for that reason doesn't have medical insurance. Pt stated he receives medical services at Alivio.  Pt would like bill payment assistance and prescription support.
notes_contact2: I spoke with Joanna Perez from HCH financial department, she informed me that pt was screened while in the hospital. She stated that pt was given a list of required documents. I informed Joanna that pt lost his ID and she stated that pt MUST have some type of identification.

notes_contact5: Pt called me back, he stated he is doing better, he stated that he spoke with Joanna and she explained to him all she needs to help him with his hospital bill. Pt stated he needs to get at least proof from the Mexican consulate that he is trying to obtain a Mexican ID. I encouraged pt to take all needed steps so he can get financial assistance from the hospital.
notes_contact6: Spoke with pt who stated he is doing well. Pt confirmed that he went to the Mexican and received proof that he is working on renovating his Consular Identification Card.  Pt wants me to help him find a PCP near his home.    Search information requested:  https://app.nowpow.com/patient/eRX/XZM4OUJ561/es

I asked if he had applied at the Department of Housing and Urban Development, and he said that he hasn't because he doesn't have an ID. Pt stated that he would like to get a job but needs an ID first.  Pt's niece asked if we would pay for pt's ID. I informed her that we only help patients find resources.  Pt stated that he has a drinking a substance abuse problem.   Pt mentioned that the Secretary of State is closed, and for that reason, he hasn't tried to get an ID. I informed pt that I renewed my driver's license last year.  I will check with the Secretary of State next week to find out when he would get an ID.
notes_contact2: I spoke with pt's niece, Passion, who stated that pt wasn't home. I asked when could I reach him, and she suggested to call him before 9:00 AM.
notes_contact3: Called pt to inform him the steps he needs to take to obtain a new stated ID. Pt informed that he doesn't have a birth certificate. I will search how to get a duplicate birth certificate.
notes_contact4: I called pt, and I spoke with pt's niece, who stated that pt wasn't at home at the moment. She suggested I call after 10;00. I called pt at 10:27; no one answered the phone. LVM
notes_contact5: I called pt, no answer. I left a voice message with the steps and costs associated with obtaining a copy of his birth certificate.
notes_contact6: I spoke with pt who stated he didn't receive the message I left. I informed pt the steps and information he needs to get a copy of his birth certificate. Pt stated he doesn't have money to pay for it or his ID or his birth certificate. I reiterated that we don't have funds to help them pay for services. Pt stated that he also needs to get a copy of his social security card, which he needs to get his birth certificate. I will find the closest social security office near pt's home.
notes_contact7: Per pt's nice, he wasn't at home; she stated he went to the clinic due to coughing.
notes_contact8: Called pt, no answer, left a message indicating what he needs to do to obtain a copy of his birth certificate.
notes_contact9: I spoke with pt who stated he is doing ok. I gave him once again the information on how to get a copy of his birth certificate; pt expressed understanding.  I informed pt that once he gets his birth certificate, he should be able to obtain the stated ID.
notes_contact10: I called pt, his niece answered the phone, and I asked to speak with pt; she asked to hold on. After 10 minutes, she returned to the phone and said that pt wasn't at home. She stated that pt as of yesterday, got a new phone number, 872-263-6441. I called that number and got no answer. LVM.

referral_notes: Per Jesus, ED CHW    Patient needs assistance getting link card.
notes_contact1: I spoke with the patient; he is recuperating from his cholecystectomy performed early this week.  Pt stated that he was feeling better. He said he has a PCP and excellent family support. He lives alone, but his family visits him often. He likes to be active, mow the lawn, or do other light tasks to be active and prevent depression.   Pt said he usually gets transportation from his insurance but has had trouble with it lately. So I gave pt Sinai's transportation number.  I asked pt if he needed help applying for the Link card, as the CSP referral form mentioned. He said that he needs help applying for Medicaid, not Link. So I will search for agencies near the patient's home that would help him apply.
notes_contact2: I called pt, no answer. LVM
notes_contact3: I spoke with pt, who stated he was admitted to MSH again. However, he didn't want to talk and asked me to call him next week.
notes_contact4: I spoke with the patient, who stated she had just returned from a doctor's visit and wasn't feeling well. He asked me if I could call him tomorrow. I agreed.
notes_contact5: I spoke with the patient, who stated that he was feeling better. I informed him of the income guidelines to receive Medicaid; he said he should qualify based on that information.  I asked him to write down the Illinois Department of Healthcare Family Services number, and he said he wasn't prepared. He couldn't find a pen and paper. He asked me to call him next week so he can be ready to write down the information.
notes_contact6: I talked with the patient and gave him the necessary information to apply for Medicaid. He also shared that he has an appointment scheduled for next week at MSH, and he hopes they will remove the draining tubes from his abdomen as it's hindering his ability to perform daily tasks.
notes_contact7: During our conversation, the patient informed me that he feels much better after attending his appointment to have one of his abdomen draining tubes. He also mentioned that he has another appointment on May 22 to get the second tube removed. When I inquired about his Medicaid application, he said he called but was put on hold and eventually hung up. I suggested he apply online, but he indicated he doesn't know how to use a computer. I advised him to ask a family member for assistance.  Since the patient had no further needs, I informed him that this was our final call. I shared my contact details and urged him to contact me if he required additional assistance.

notes_contact1: Patient was discharged from the HCH this morning. I visited the Police station where he has been residing with his family for the past few days. I successfully found the patient and provided him with toiletries. In addition, I also offered toiletries to other immigrants residing in the police station. The patient was happy to see me.
notes_contact2: I went to the police station to deliver clothing and shoes to the patient and his wife. When I met them, they expressed gratitude for the items I provided.
notes_contact3: The patient contacted me; he shared that he was taken to Stoger Hospital on Sunday and stayed there for 9 hours. Unfortunately, he found the staff at that hospital rude and felt that the treatment and friendliness he received did not compare to what he experienced at HCH. Currently, the patient is staying in a shelter and receiving medication for his DM2 and cellulitis. He has scheduled appointments with a dentist, eye doctor, and diabetes specialist. The patient expressed gratitude for the clothing I provided for him and his spouse.
notes_contact4: I had a conversation with the patient, and he reported that his foot is healing nicely and the foot infection has cleared up. He has received medical treatment and eye care. He resides in a park on 31st and Kostner but will soon move to a hotel. He appears to be content and optimistic about his situation.
notes_contact5: The patient contacted and report feeling better. He shared that he was still residing in the park and expressed concerns about the status of his Medicaid application. I assured him I would follow up with Bolder to check the application's progress.
notes_contact6: I updated the patient on my conversation with Joanna Perez from Bolder. She informed me that she was waiting for a document from the doctor who treated the patient in the hospital. She assured me that she would email the doctor today to remind him to submit the form. She also mentioned that if the patient is approved for Medicaid, the medical coverage will be backdated to February 2023.
notes_contact7: I went to the patient to the park where pt has been staying. I brought some clothes for him and his family. He informed me that his leg was healing well. He has been selling water bottles on the streets to earn a few dollars daily. He has an appt with the ophthalmologist this week. The patient and his wife were thrilled to see me and grateful for the small gifts I brought.
notes_contact8: I spoke with the patient, who said he went to drop off some documents at the ICE. He and his family have an appointment with ICE in August. Pt received an ID. He has an appt with a doctor today and next week with ortho. He still depends on a wheelchair for mobility.
notes_contact9: During our conversation, the patient expressed that his health is improving. He mentioned that he's receiving help to secure an apartment in the near future. Additionally, he joyfully shared the news that his daughter had a baby last week. The patient seemed optimistic and hopeful about what lies ahead.
notes_contact10: I talked with a patient who shared some good news with me. He is going to move to a new apartment on September 15. He also mentioned that he got a car. He seemed very happy about it.     During our conversation, he mentioned that he had received medical services from Cook County recently but was not satisfied with the quality of care he received. I asked him if he had Medicaid, and he told me he had a number that he used at Cook County for his medical services.     I suggested he make an appointment with a physician at Sinai Health System for better care and gave him the number for Sinai's Central Scheduling. I will follow up with him later to check if he was able to schedule an appointment with Sinai.    10/31/23 13:01 I called pt, no answer.

referral_notes: Per SW,  rental assistance, food pantry
notes_contact1: I spoke with the patient, who stated that he was seen at MSH on Monday, July 31, to follow up on his left foot amputation. Pt said that, at the moment, he could not work but hopes to return once his doctor deems it safe to do so. The patient shared that he anticipates receiving a prosthetic foot in the future.  The patient mentioned that he requires assistance finding rental support and information regarding food pantries. I provided the requested information to the patient over the phone and sent it to him via text.  I let the patient know about his scheduled appointments, which includes his upcoming appointment at HCH diabetes clinic tomorrow, August 3rd, at 10:00.
notes_contact2: I called pt, no answered. LVM.
notes_contact3: I spoke with the patient, who said he was feeling much better. He informed me that the food pantries I gave him one is undergoing construction and are closed. The other one they don't answer the phone. I checked the Greater Chicago Food Depository and provided the patient with four additional places near his home.   He said he had called regarding the rental assistance, but no one answered. I called the City of Chicago Rental Assistance Program and was informed that they currently don't have funds. Pt will need to call in October.  I located another option, the Spanish Coalition for Housing. I called to make sure someone would answer the phone, and they did. I gave pt the information, and said he would call.
notes_contact4: I spoke with the patient, who said he was doing well. He said he could contact the food pantries and the Spanish Coalition for Housing, with positive results.  I informed pt of his upcoming appointments.  Pt asked if I could help him with job searching. I provided pt with a list of agencies to help him search for employment.  NowPow eRx code: MQM4OX35LB
notes_contact5: I spoke with the patient, who stated that he was doing well. He said he still hasn't been able to get rental assistance; his last try was yesterday when he called the Salvation Army. He will call them back later this week, and hopefully, they will be able to help him. He said he is visiting the food pantries and getting food from them.   He is aware of his upcoming wound clinic appointments.
notes_contact6: I spoke with the patient, who stated that he feels good. He was seen at the wound clinic today and said his wounds are healing well. Pt mentioned that he is getting food from the food pantries I recommended to him.  I informed pt that today was my last call and asked him to contact me if he needed additional help.

I inquired if he had seen a doctor, and he replied that he had an upcoming appointment with a hand specialist at Northwestern on Tuesday, August 22nd. The patient expressed that his hand pain prevented him from working or doing anything. He also mentioned that he wanted to apply for SNAP benefits. When I offered the number to apply for benefits, he questioned how he would make the call with his hand hurting. I reminded him that he was speaking to me on the phone and could make the call. I then directed him to the website abe.illinois.gov to apply for benefits online.
notes_contact4: During the conversation with the patient, he confirmed that he underwent the hand surgery as planned. He shared that the surgery was successful, and he was scheduled to begin physical therapy next week. The patient expressed frustration over being unable to work, and I advised him to focus on his physical therapy, which will enable him to return to work soon. The patient had no additional social needs, and I requested that he contact me if he required further assistance.

However, the clinic told her she would have to pay cash for the treatments since she didn't have medical insurance. She also mentioned that she gets nervous or anxious on the streets. I recommended that she tell her lawyer these problems; based on her pending lawsuit, he should be able to advise her on what to do or where to go for treatment.    The patient also mentioned that she hasn't worked since her accident, and she's finding it challenging to buy food. To help her out, I provided her with information about food pantries near her home.

notes_contact6: I spoke with the patient, who said she didn't answer my calls because she lost her phone service, she couldn't afford to pay for her service. She also informed me that the attorney's assistant had promised to send her for physical therapy, but she had not received any communication from them recently. She said perhaps they called her when she lost her phone service. I advised her to contact the attorney and let him know about her situation, as she has lost her job, has no income, and hasn't been able to see the therapist yet. I suggested she tell the attorney that it may be best for her to find another attorney because she has yet to get the answers she expected from him.
notes_contact7: She was in a very positive mood because she started her PT sessions. She gets four sessions per week at home. She also went to her former employer and was told she may return to work in January 2024.

She mentioned that she spoke with her doctor, and he didn't see much improvement, so he said that she may need a new surgery soon. She has an upcoming appointment with the surgeon next week. She still needs to work and is afraid she won't have rent money available. I suggested she talk to her lawyer and mention this situation to get his advice.

I advised her to contact the Chilean Consulate in Chicago to see if there is something they can do to help her. I gave her the phone number and address of the consulate.

I suggested she contact her lawyer for them to arrange transport for her. She said she often feels down. I suggested she start learning English to be occupied; I gave her information about free online programs. She said she would give it a try.
